sh
# Interpreter for 'vpn-switch session refresh' command
# Terminal function that generates shell commands to reconcile interface ownership
#
# Default value: "sh"
#   Compares the peers actually loaded on each live interface (ground truth)
#   against each session's stored config, then re-points session/latest-$interface
#   to the session whose config is genuinely loaded. Repairs ownership drift so
#   'session list' reports the session that is really live.
#
# When ownership drifts:
#   - A resume re-points latest-$interface but `wg-quick up` fails because the
#     interface is already up with a different config
#   - disconnect does not remove the ownership symlink, leaving stale ownership
#   - Concurrent start/stop operations race on the ownership symlink
#
# Session refresh workflow:
#   1. Reads loaded WireGuard peers per interface (read-only, no root needed)
#   2. Finds the session whose stored PublicKey set matches the loaded peers
#   3. Re-points latest-$interface to that session (or removes it if the
#      interface is down); leaves ownership untouched when peers are unreadable
#
# Operates only on symlinks in the user-owned session/ directory - no sudo.
#
# Example usage:
#   vpn-switch session refresh     # Reconcile ownership against reality
#
# Advanced - dry-run mode (preview commands without executing):
#   echo "cat" > .env/local/VPN_SWITCH_INTERPRETER_session_refresh
#   vpn-switch session refresh
